/** \page xCrystal Inputing Crystal Structures and Lattices

    <h1> Inputing a Structure </h1>
    \anchor xstructure
   Structures should be enclosed in a \xe\<Structure\>\ex ... \xe\</Structure\>\ex
 * tags as follows  inputed in the following way:
    \code
    <Structure scale=6.2>
        <Cell>
            <column x="0.000000" y="1.000000" z="1.000000" />
            <column x="1.000000" y="0.000000" z="1.000000" />
            <column x="1.500000" y="1.500000" z="0.000000" />
        </Cell>
        <Atom x="0.000000" y="0.000000" z="0.000000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="0.500000" y="0.500000" z="0.000000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="1.000000" y="1.000000" z="0.000000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="0.500000" y="0.000000" z="0.500000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="1.000000" y="0.500000" z="0.500000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="1.500000" y="1.000000" z="0.500000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="0.000000" y="0.500000" z="0.500000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="0.500000" y="1.000000" z="0.500000" type="Au" />
        <Atom x="1.000000" y="1.500000" z="0.500000" type="Pd" />
        <Atom x="0.500000" y="0.500000" z="1.000000" type="Pd" />
        <Atom x="1.000000" y="1.000000" z="1.000000" type="Pd" />
        <Atom x="1.500000" y="1.500000" z="1.000000" type="Pd" />
    </Structure>
    \endcode
    The following XML tags have been introduced:
   \secreflist
     \refitem TagStructure \<Structure\>
     \refitem Tagcell \<Cell\>
     \refitem Tagcolumn \<column/\>
     \refitem TagAtom \<Atom/\>
   \endsecreflist

   \section TagStructure \<Structure\>
   \addindex \<Structure\>
   Contains information pertaining to a single structure. It expects a complete
   \ref Tagcell as well as at least one \ref TagAtom.
   It can contain the following attributes
     \param scale scaling factor (&Aring;) with
         respect to which positions and cell-vectors are given. Defaults to 1.
     \param energy In some cases, will contain the
         "energy" of the structure. Not necessary for input.
     \param Pi Pi-file name of the stucture, or any other
         name you want. Not really of any use.

   \section Tagcell \<Cell\>
   \addindex \<Cell\>
   Defines the unit-cell vectors of the \ref TagStructure 
   tag whithin which it is found.  It does not expect any attributes.  The
   cell-vectors are defined using three \ref Tagcolumn tags.

   \section Tagcolumn \<column/\>
   \addindex \<column/\>
   Defines a column within a 3x3 matrix. It contains the following attributes
   \param x first coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param y second coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param z third coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param freeze Allows to "freeze" \a x, \a y, \a z, coordinates, or a
             combination thereof, such that the frozen coordinates are
             untouched during minimization. \a freeze is optional.

   \section TagAtom \<Atom/\> 
   Defines an atomic site and its occupation of the \ref TagStructure within
   which it is found. Only attribute \a x, \a y, \a z are mandatory for all
   applications. Attribute \a type is required for anything not GA. 
    
   \param x first cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param y second cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param z third cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagStructure's \a scale attribute
   \param type Atomic type. It can be a numerical value (generally \f$\pm1\f$)
          or an atomic symbol
   \param freeze Allows to "freeze" \a x, \a y, \a z, or \a t coordinates, or a
             combination thereof, such that the frozen coordinates are
             untouched during minimization. \a t stands for type. \a freeze is optional. 
   \param site Should be an integer \f$i\in[0, N]\f$ where \f$N\f$ is the
          number of sites declared in \ref TagLattice. The index \f$i\f$
          corresponds to the ordering of \ref Tagsite tags in the XML input. 
   
   <h1> Inputing a lattice </h1>
    \anchor xxlattice
    You can input a lattice in the following way:
    \code
    <Lattice>
        <column x="0.00000000" y="0.50000000" z="0.50000000" />
        <column x="0.50000000" y="0.00000000" z="0.50000000" />
        <column x="0.50000000" y="0.50000000" z="0.00000000" />
        <site x="0.00000000" y="0.00000000" z="0.00000000">
            <atom type="Au" />
            <atom type="Pd" />
        </site>
    </Lattice>
    \endcode
    \note Including a lattice  in your input is generally <em>not</em> an
       option. Furthermore, the lattice input must be coherent with whatever \ref
       TagStructure which may be required.

    \ref Tagcolumn has already been introduced previously. This variation
      accepts the exact same attributes. Note that for some unknowable reason, \ref
      Tagcolumn tags are not enclosed in a \ref Tagcell tag when defining a \ref  TagLattice tag...

    The following new XML tags have been introduced:
   \secreflist
     \refitem TagLattice \<Lattice\>
     \refitem Tagsite \<site\>
     \refitem Tagatom \<atom/\>
   \endsecreflist
    
   \section TagLattice \<Lattice\>
   \addindex \<Lattice\>
   Contains information pertaining to a lattice type.  In addition to three
   \ref Tagcolumn tag's, at least one \ref Tagsite is expected.
   It can include the following attributes
     \param scale scaling factor (&Aring;) with
         respect to which positions and unit-cell vectors are given. Defaults to 1.
   
   \section Tagsite \<site\>
   \addindex \<site\>
      Defines a lattice site, which may contain one or more \ref Tagatom tags. 
      It accepts the following attributes.
     \param x first cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagLattice's \a scale attribute
     \param y second cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagLattice's \a scale attribute
     \param z third cartesian coordinate scaled by ref TagLattice's \a scale attribute
     \param freeze Allows to "freeze" \a x, \a y, \a z, or \a t coordinates, or a
               combination thereof, such that the frozen coordinates are
               untouched during minimization. \a t stands for type. \a freeze is optional.
   \warning \a freeze in a \ref TagLattice can only be used to freeze all atoms
            of a particular site in a structure if attribute \a site of the relevant \ref
            TagAtom tags have been set in the corresponding \ref TagStructure.

   \section Tagatom \<atom/\>
     \addindex \<atom/\>
      Adds a possible atomic-type to the lattice \ref Tagsite within which it is found.
      Its attributes are:
     \param type Atomic type which should be inputed as an atomic symbol.
*/

